# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ale
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ale/abbey-beers] In 2016, UNESCO inscribed Belgian beer culture on their list of the intangible cultural heritage of humanity.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] In Belgium, beer was already produced in the Roman era, as evidenced by the excavation of a brewery and malthouse from the 3rd and 4th centuries AD at Ronchinne.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] During the Early and High Middle Ages, beer was produced with gruit, a mix of herbs and spices that was first mentioned in 974 when the bishop of Liège was granted the right to sell it at Fosses-la-Ville.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] From the 14th century onwards, gruit was replaced by hops, after the example of imported beers from northern Germany and Holland.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] After that, several Belgian towns developed their own types of beer for export to other regions, most notably the white beer of Leuven and Hoegaarden, the *caves* of Lier and the *uitzet* of Ghent.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] In recent years, the use of gruit has experienced a revival, particularly among homebrewers and eventually by commercial breweries.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] For instance, Gageleer brews a beer using sweet gale (*Myrica gale*) based on a medieval recipe.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Monasteries played only a small role in beer production and mostly brewed for their own consumption and that of their guests.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Monastic brewing would only receive some renown from the late 19th century onwards, when the Trappists of Chimay produced a brown beer that was commercially available.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] In 1885, a change in legislation made brewing of German-style bottom-fermenting beers viable in Belgium, and it was only from then that large industrial-scale brewing in Belgium took off.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] During the 20th century the number of breweries in Belgium declined from 3223 breweries in 1900 to only 106 breweries in 1993.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Yet, a number of traditional beer styles, such as white beer, lambic and Flemish old brown were preserved, while new local, top-fermented styles developed, such as *spéciale belge*, abbey beer and Belgian strong ale.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] In 1988, the country's two biggest breweries, Artois and Piedboeuf, formally merged to become Interbrew, then the world's 18th biggest brewer, which was to merge with AmBev in 2004 to become today's AB InBev, the biggest beer producing company in the world.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] In Belgium, four types of fermentation methods are used for the brewing of beer, which is unique in the world.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Belgian beers have a range of colours, brewing methods, and alcohol levels.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Beers brewed in Trappist monasteries are termed Trappist beers.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] For a beer to qualify for Trappist certification, the brewery must be in a monastery, the monks must play a role in its production and the policies and the profits from the sale must be used to support the monastery or social programs outside.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Only ten monasteries currently meet these qualifications, five of which are in Belgium, two in the Netherlands, one in Austria, one in Italy and one in the United Kingdom.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Trappist beer is a controlled term of origin: it tells where the beers come from, it is not the name of a beer style.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Beyond their being mostly warm fermented, Trappist beers have very little in common stylistically.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] In addition to the above, a lower-strength beer is sometimes brewed for consumption by the brothers (*patersbier*) or sold on site.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] For example, *l’Orval Vert* (or *Petit Orval*, also known as "Green Orval" or "Small Orval") is served to the monks and guests of the Orval Abbey and can only be consumed on tap in the nearby *À l’Ange Gardien* abbey café.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] The designation "abbey beers" (*Bières d'Abbaye* or *Abdijbier*) originally applied to any monastic or monastic-style beer.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] After introduction of an official Trappist beer designation by the International Trappist Association in 1997, it came to mean products similar in style or presentation to monastic beers.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] The requirements for registration under the logo include the monastery having control over certain aspects of the commercial operation, and a proportion of profits going to the abbey or to its designated charities.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Monastic orders other than the Trappists can be and are included in this arrangement.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] The "Abbey beer" logo and quality label is no longer used for beers given the name of a fictitious abbey, a vaguely monastic branding or a saint name without mentioning a specific monastery.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Some brewers may produce abbey-style beers such as dubbel or tripel, using such names but will refrain from using the term Abbey beer in their branding.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] What connoisseurs now recognize as Trappist breweries began operations in 1838.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Several monasteries, however, maintained "working" breweries for 500+ years before the French regime disrupted religious life (1795–1799).
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Even then, some Abbey beers such as Affligem Abbey, whose name now appears on beers made by the Heineken-owned Affligem Brewery, resumed brewing from "working" monasteries until the occupation of most of Belgium in World War I.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Commercial Abbey beers first appeared during Belgium's World War I recovery.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Although Abbey beers do not conform to rigid brewing styles, most tend to include the most recognizable and distinctive Trappist styles of brune (Belgian brown ale, aka dubbel), strong pale ale or tripel, and blonde ale or blond.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Modern abbey breweries range from microbreweries to international giants, but at least one beer writer warns against assuming that closeness of connection with a real monastery confirms a product's quality.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] This style makes up the bulk of beer production and consumption in Belgium.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Belgian Pilsners are not particularly distinctive or renowned by connoisseurs.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] The top brands include Jupiler (within Belgium) and Stella Artois (both brewed by Inbev), Maes pils and Cristal (both brewed by the Alken Maes branch of Heineken).
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Stella Artois, originating in Leuven, Belgium; is distributed globally.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] The Pilsnerbeer is which is popularly called "*pintje*" (in Flemish, from English "pint" but in volume only 0.25 cl or roughly 1/2 pint) or "*choppe*" (in French) in Belgium, was the basis of the "*fluitjesbier*" distributed during the German occupation in WWII and under rationing.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] This "*fluitjesbier*" was watered down to about 0.8° (compared to fruitjuice which can have up to 1.5° due to natural fermentation).
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Bock is a strong lager of German origin.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Some Belgian brewers have produced bock-style beers what makes it a style applicable to Belgium.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] This type of beer, commonly called *witbier* in Dutch, *bière blanche* in French and *wheat beer* in English, originated in the Flemish part of Belgium in the Middle Ages.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Traditionally, it is made with a mixture of wheat and barley.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Before hops became widely available in Europe, beers were flavoured with a mixture of herbs called gruit.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] In the later years of the Middle Ages, hops were added to the gruit.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] That mixture continues today in most Belgian white beers.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] The production of this type of beer in Belgium had nearly ended by the late 1950s.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] In the town of Hoegaarden, the last *witbier* brewery, Tomsin, closed its doors in 1955.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] However, ten years later, a young farmer by the name of Pierre Celis in the same village decided to try reviving the beer.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] In 1966, Celis began brewing a "witbier" in his farmhouse.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Ultimately, the Hoegaarden brewery took the name of the village and became successful, gaining international prominence.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] For instance, in 2018, only 8% of the 1.3 million hectoliters of beer produced annually were intended for the Belgian market.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Some notable current examples are Celis White, Blanche de Namur and Watou's Wit.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Their alcohol strength is about 5–6 percent ABV, and these beers can be quite refreshing, especially during the warm summer months.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] The herb mixture traditionally includes coriander and bitter orange peel, among other herbs.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] White beers also have a moderate light grain sweetness from the wheat used.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] In recent times, brewers have been making fruit flavoured wheat beers.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] These are a light variation on pale ale, often made with pilsner malt.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Some beer writers regard blonde and golden ales as distinct styles, while others do not.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Duvel is the archetypal Belgian blonde ale, and one of the most popular bottled beers in the country as well as being well known internationally.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Its name means "Devil" and some other blonde beers follow the theme—Satan, Lucifer and Judas for example.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] The style is popular with Walloon brewers, the slightly hazy Moinette being the best-known example.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Chouffe can be considered a spiced version (with coriander).
[src:ale/abbey-beers] A few Belgian beers are pale and assertively hopped.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] De Ranke's XX Bitter has a British-style name.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Arabier from De Dolle Brouwers.Brouwerij Van Eecke's Poperings Hommelbier, another example, hails from Belgium's hop-growing district.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] From Lambic four kinds of beer are produced: Lambic, Gueuze, Fruit Lambic, and Faro.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] These are beers similar to the traditional pale ales of England, although less bitterly hopped.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] A notable example is the 5% ABV De Koninck brand, with its distinctive half-spherical glasses (called 'bollekes').
[src:ale/abbey-beers] It is popular in its native city of Antwerp.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Some, such as Vieux Temps, were based on British styles to please troops stationed in Belgium during World War I.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Others were introduced by the UK-born brewer George Maw Johnson in the late 19th century.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] A very strong *ambrée* is brewed by "Bush" (*Dubuisson*), another brewery influenced by British styles.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Walloon amber or *ambrée* ale, such a Gauloise Ambrée, is considered to be somewhat distinct by some beer writers, and to be influenced by the French version of the *ambrée* style.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Tripel is a term used originally by brewers in the Low Countries to describe a strong pale ale, and became associated with *Westmalle Tripel*.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] The style of Westmalle's *Tripel* and the name was widely copied by the breweries of Belgium, then the term spread to the US and other countries.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] *Gulden Draak* was awarded the best-tasting beer in the world in 1998 by the *American Tasting Institute* (now ChefsBest).
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Dubbel (*double*) has a characteristic brown colour.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] It is one of the classic Abbey/Trappist types, having been developed in the 19th century at the Trappist monastery in Westmalle.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Today, some commercial brewers using abbey names call their strong brown beers "Dubbel".
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Typically, a dubbel is between 6 and 8% abv.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] In addition to the dubbels made by most Trappist breweries, examples include St.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Bernardus Pater, Adelardus Dubbel, Maredsous 8 and Witkap Dubbel.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Dubbels are characteristically bottle conditioned.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] The result is a mildly strong 'drinking' beer with a deep reddish-brown colour and a distinctly acidic, sour yet fruity and mouthy taste.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] This style is closely related to Oud bruin.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] This style, aged in wooden casks, is a cousin to the sour "Flemish Red" style.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Examples include Rodenbach, Goudenband and Petrus.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Regular bruin or brune beers such as Grottenbier are darker than amber ales, less sour than Flemish brown ale, and less strong than dubbel.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] These sweet, heavy-bodied brown ales represent a style which originated in the British Isles.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] The Caledonian theme is usually heavily emphasized with tartan and thistles appearing on labels.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Examples include Gordon's, Scotch de Silly and La Chouffe Mc Chouffe.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Belgian stouts subdivide into sweeter and drier, and stronger and weaker versions.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Examples include Callewaerts and Ellezelloise Hercule.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] The sweeter versions resemble the almost-defunct British style "milk stout", while the stronger ones are sometimes described as Imperial stouts.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Champagne style beers are generally ales that are finished "à la méthode originale" for champagne.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Examples include Grottenbier, DeuS and Malheur Bière Brut.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] They receive a second fermentation much like Champagne does and are stored for several months "sûr lie" while the fermentation lasts.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] This creates the smaller, softer bubbles that we know from Champagne, but maintains the beer flavour and style.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] In Belgium "Grand Cru" is more often used than "Quadrupel", these beers are a mostly a blend of brews, which is often refermented as a blend.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Saison (French for "season") is the name originally given to refreshing, low-alcohol beers brewed seasonally in Wallonia, the French-speaking region of Belgium.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] First seen in early 19th century Liège, saisons gained notoriety as a luxury beer in 20th century Hainaut brewed by city and countryside brewers alike.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] By the 1980s, they were only produced on the countryside.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Modern-day saisons are also brewed in other countries, particularly USA, and are generally bottle conditioned, with an average range of 5 to 8% ABV, though saisons at the more traditional 3.5% strength can still be found.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Although saison has been described as an endangered style, there has been a rise in interest in this style in recent years, with Saison Dupont being named "the Best Beer in the World" by the magazine *Men's Journal* in July 2005.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] A related style known as a grisette was brewed with a lower ABV and with wheat added.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Many breweries produce special beers during December.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Most contain more alcohol than the brewery's other types of beer and may also contain spicing.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] An annual beer festival in Essen near Antwerp focuses on this type of beer with over 190 beers available for tasting in 2014.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Some brewers that are not Lambic-brewers make fruit beers in a similar process as the Fruit Lambic beers.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] All brewers of this style make fruit lambic.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Many brewers of top fermentation beers such as Belgian golden ales, ambers and Flemish old brown beers, that produce beers that usually go through a multiple stage fermentation process, are catching on to the trend to make fruit beers.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] The process starts after the first fermentation of the wort, when sometimes sugar is added to referment the beer on wooden casks.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] To make fruit beer the fruit, juice or syrup is added (instead of sugar) to the first brew and refermented, these may be termed fruit lambics or fruit beers, depending on the type of first brew.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Beer that has fruit syrup or fruit lemonade added after (the final stage of) fermentation, in other words as a flavouring, are termed "Radlers" ("Shandy" in the UK) definitely not fruit beer.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Beers above 7%, such as tripels or strong dubbels, are referred to in some sources as Belgian strong ale, although this is not a name used by Belgian brewers.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Belgian beers have a wide range of styles and brewing methods and are almost always served in unique, branded glassware.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Each glass is designed to enhance the beer’s taste and aroma, often featuring the brewery’s logo or a beer-specific design.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Belgian "heavy" or "special" beers (stronger or bottled beers) are usually served in more elaborate branded beer glassware.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Some glasses are etched on the bottom; typically with the brewery’s logo, to nucleate a stream of bubbles for maintaining a nice head.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Unless the bar is out of the specific glass that goes with that beer it is usually served in its own glass.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Most bartenders or waitresses will apologize if the beer comes in a different glass.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Pils (pilsner) or pale lager, remains the most widely produced and consumed beer style in Belgium.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] One of the most typical Belgian pilsner glasses is the ribbed glass, often referred to as the *ribbelke* or *ribbelglas*.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] The Belgian pilsner glass originated between 1860 and 1900.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Its ribbed base was designed to minimize heat transfer from the drinker’s hand, preventing the beer from warming.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Additionally, the glass’s tall, narrow, and straight shape is suited to pilsner beers due to their lower foaming protein content, necessitating a smaller diameter to maintain an appropriate head.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] A regional variation is the *Boerke* glass, which translates to "small farmer".
[src:ale/abbey-beers] The question of which glass is best suited for Belgian pilsner remains a subject of debate, influenced by factors such as personal preference, brand loyalty, tradition, regional customs, and differing opinions among Belgians.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] One of the more common types is the tulip glass.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] A tulip glass not only helps trap the aroma, but also aids in maintaining large heads, creating a visual and olfactory sensation.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] The body is bulbous, but the top flares out to form a lip which helps foam head retention.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] A vessel similar to a champagne flute is the preferred serving vessel for Belgian (fruit) Lambics, Gueuze and fruit beers.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] The narrow shape helps maintain carbonation, while providing a strong aromatic front.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Flute glasses display the lively carbonation, sparkling colour, and soft lacing of this distinct style.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Traditionally, lambic beers including gueuze and fruit lambics are served in a tall glass resembling the ribbed pilsner glass.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] However, the edges and base of the lambic glass are significantly thicker; which originated from the old custom of grinding sugar at the bottom of the glass before serving, allowing drinkers to sweeten the beer to their taste, as lambic styles are known for their intense sourness.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] The glass is commonly referred to as a *lambiekstoemper* (or "lambic stomper"), a name that reflects the practice of crushing sugar with a tool similar to a cocktail muddler.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Chalices and goblets are large, stemmed, bowl-shaped glasses mainly associated with Trappist and Abbey ales.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] The distinction between goblet and chalice is typically in the glass thickness.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Goblets tend to be more delicate and thin, while the chalice is heavy and thick walled.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] However, a more recent addition, though not traditionally Belgian, is the TeKu beer glass, developed in 2006 by Teo Musso and Kuaska (hence the acronym).
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Designed as a universal beer glass, it has since been embraced by the craft beer community, particularly for styles such as pale ales, IPAs, stouts...
[src:ale/abbey-beers] In addition to the profusion of glasses provided by brewers, some Belgian beer cafés serve beer in their own "house" glassware.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] The majority of Belgian beer brands are sold in reusable bottles.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Draught beers tend mostly to be pale lagers, wheat beers, regional favourites such as kriek in Brussels or De Koninck in Antwerp; and the occasional one-off.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] These days, Belgian beers are sold in brown- (or sometimes dark green-) tinted glass bottles (to avoid negative effects of light on the beverage) and sealed with a cork, a metal crown cap, or sometimes both.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Some beers are bottle conditioned, meaning reseeded with yeast so that an additional fermentation may take place.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Different bottle sizes exist: 25 cl, 33 cl, 37.5 cl, 75 cl and multiples of 75.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] (8, 12, 24 or multiples of 24 fl. oz.) The 37.5 cl size is usually for lambics.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Other beers are generally bottled in 25 or 33 cl format (depending on brands).
[src:ale/abbey-beers] The bigger bottles (75 cl) are sold almost in every food shop but customers do not always have an extensive choice.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Bottles larger than 75 cl are named following the terminology used for champagne and are limited in quantity.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] In Brussels or Walloon Belgian cafés, you can order orders a *demi* (English: "half"), which is a 50 cl draught beer.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] The prominence of the Belgian beer culture is reflected in the extensive range of beers offered in nearly every café across the country.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Belgium contains thousands of cafés that offer a wide selection of beers, a typical beer menu ranges from at least half a dozen draught beers and two dozen bottled beers of different types in a neighborhood café, to over 1000 in a specialist beer café.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Although many major brands of beer are available at most supermarkets, off-licences located throughout the country generally offer a far wider selection, albeit at somewhat higher prices.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] In 2024, Belgium exported around 70% of its beer production, amounting to approximately 14 million hectoliters.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Some draught-beer brands produced by AB InBev like Stella Artois, Hoegaarden and Leffe are available in several European countries.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Aside from these, mostly bottled beer is exported across Europe.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Cafés, exclusively or primarily offering Belgian beers, exist beyond Belgium in Australia, New Zealand, Canada, France, the United Kingdom and the United States, amongst others.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Some beer festivals outside Belgium have a Belgian beer bar as an alternative to local products.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] In North America, a growing number of draught Belgian beer brands have started to become available, often at "Belgian Bars".
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Such brands include Brasserie Brunehaut, Karmeliet, Kwak, Maredsous, Mont Saint-Aubert, Delirium, Palm, Rodenbach and St.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] A number of traditional Belgian dishes use beer as an ingredient.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] One is *carbonade* (French) or *stoverij* or *stoofvlees* (Dutch), a stew of beef cooked in beer, similar to Boeuf bourguignon.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] The beer used is typically the regional speciality—lambic in Brussels, De Koninck in Antwerp, and so on—so that the taste of the dish varies.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] *In't Spinnekopke*, Brussels, and *Den Dyver*, Bruges are famed for their beer cookery.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] In 1998 Anheuser-Busch InBev started a worldwide chain of bars/restaurants, Belgian Beer Cafe, serving typical Belgian dishes combined with Belgian Beer.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Beer writers who have written extensively on Belgian beer include Belgians Peter Crombeq, Gert van Lierde and Erik Verdonck, and Britons Michael Jackson and Tim Webb.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] The following list contains beers that are brewed in Belgium.
[src:ale/abbey-beers] Not to be confused with "Belgian style" beers that are produced in other countries, and may or may not resemble a style that is specific to Belgium.
[src:ale/adjuncts] In brewing, **adjuncts** are unmalted grains (such as barley, wheat, maize, rice, rye, and oats) or grain products used in brewing beer which supplement the main mash ingredient (such as malted barley).
[src:ale/adjuncts] This is often done with the intention of cutting costs, but sometimes also to create an additional feature, such as better foam retention, flavours or nutritional value or additives.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Both solid and liquid adjuncts are commonly used.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Ingredients which are standard for certain beers, such as wheat in a wheat beer, may be termed adjuncts when used in beers which could be made without them — such as adding wheat to a pale ale for the purpose of creating a lasting head.
[src:ale/adjuncts] The sense here is that the ingredient is additional and strictly unnecessary, though it may be beneficial and attractive.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Under the Bavarian *Reinheitsgebot* purity law it would be considered that an adjunct is *any* beer ingredient other than water, barley, hops, and yeast; this, however, is an antiquated view.
[src:ale/adjuncts] This purity law originated in 16th-century Germany and did not initially include yeast due to the fact that it had not been discovered yet.
[src:ale/adjuncts] The term adjunct is often used to refer to corn, rice, oats, unmalted barley and rye.
[src:ale/adjuncts] The use of ingredients as substitutes for the main starch source is where the term adjunct is most often used.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Adjuncts can be broadly classified according to the physical form in which they are used into solids and liquid syrups.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Barley is used as an un-malted grain at up to 10% of the grist.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Barley provides both carbohydrates and proteins to the wort; on the negative side, the cell walls of the un-malted barley contain high levels of beta-glucans that affect wort viscosity and create haze problems in the bright beer.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Barley is also used in the mash as roasted barley to provide colour to the beer.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Cassava is a novel adjunct used in Africa either as a wet cake or as a purified starch.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Corn is commonly used in the production of American-style pale lagers, particularly malt liquor.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Corn is generally used in brewing as corn syrup, and as such is highly fermentable.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Corn is cheaper than barley, so it is used as a cost-saving measure.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Oatmeal stouts usually do not specifically taste of oats.
[src:ale/adjuncts] The smoothness of oatmeal stouts comes from the high content of proteins, lipids, and gums imparted by the use of oats.
[src:ale/adjuncts] The gums increase the viscosity and body adding to the sense of smoothness.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Rice is sometimes used in the production of pale lagers, most notably Anheuser-Busch's Budweiser.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Anheuser-Busch is the largest North American buyer of U.S. rice.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Rice may be used to lighten the body and the mouthfeel, or increase alcohol content, or add a little sweetness.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Rye is used in *roggenbiers* from Germany and in rye beers from America.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Rye is notoriously difficult to brew with, so most rye beers only include a small amount of rye.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Rye provides a spicy flavour to beer and dramatically increases head formation.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Sorghum is used in Africa as a local ingredient saving on expensive imported malt and developing the local agricultural sector.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Sorghum has a high gelatinisation temperature and is added to a mash cooker to gelatinise the starch before adding to the mash tun.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Sorghum has been used for hundreds of years as the main ingredient in many of the indigenous traditional African beers.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Sorghum can be used in the malted or the un-malted form.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Wheat is used in German and American wheat beers, in lambic and other Belgian ales, and in English ales.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Wheat lightens the body, improves head retention, and provides a tart flavour.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Wheat beers are often served with fruit syrups or slices of lemon in the US and Germany.
[src:ale/adjuncts] In England, beans were occasionally used as an ingredient in beer brewing.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Sugar adjuncts provide only carbohydrates and if used at high levels will result in wort lacking in amino acids and this may lead to poor yeast growth causing tailing fermentations and poor yeast crops.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Primings sugars such as maple syrup, honey, and molasses are common in craft beers and homebrew.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Candi sugar is a common ingredient in strong Belgian ales, where it increases the beer's strength while keeping the body fairly light; dark varieties of candi sugar also affect the colour and flavour of the beer.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Caramel syrup is used to provide colour to brews and can either be added in the wort kettle or at filtration when needed to correct low beer colours.
[src:ale/adjuncts] This caramel is not sweet and provides little or no fermentable extract.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Honey is a primary fermentable in mead, and can be used for flavour (though also supplying some fermentable sugar) in beer.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Sucrose may come from sugar-cane or from sugar-beet.
[src:ale/adjuncts] A number of traditional beer styles are brewed with spices.
[src:ale/adjuncts] For example, Belgian *witbier* and German *gose* are brewed with coriander, Finnish *sahti* is brewed with juniper berries, and traditional beers in Britain are brewed with honey and spices.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Also, some strong winter beers are flavoured with nutmeg or cinnamon, while ginger is a popular flavouring for a range of beers.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Many commercially available pumpkin ales are made with pumpkin pie spices without any actual pumpkin.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Spices may be added to the wort during the boil or spices or spice extract may be added at any time during fermentation depending on desired results.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Other, less common flavourings include chocolate, coffee, milk, chili peppers and even oysters.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Beer may be brewed with a fruit or vegetable adjunct or flavouring.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Fruits have been used as a beer adjunct or flavouring for centuries, especially with Belgian lambic styles.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Cherry, raspberry, and peach are a common addition to this style of beer.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Modern breweries may add only flavoured extracts to the finished product, rather than actually fermenting the fruit.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Pumpkin-flavoured beers are brewed seasonally in the autumn in North America.
[src:ale/adjuncts] Chile pepper is used to flavour pale lagers.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] France, alcohol by volume is often referred to as **degrees Gay-Lussac** (after the French chemist Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac), although there is a slight difference since the Gay-Lussac convention uses the International Standard Atmosphere value for temperature, 15 °C (59 °F).
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] Mixing two solutions of alcohol of different strengths usually causes a change in volume.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] Mixing pure water with a solution less than 24% by mass causes a slight increase in total volume, whereas the mixing of two solutions above 24% causes a decrease in volume.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] The phenomenon of volume changes due to mixing dissimilar solutions is called "partial molar volume".
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] Water and ethanol are both polar solvents.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] When water is added to ethanol, the smaller water molecules are attracted to the ethanol's hydroxyl group, and each molecule alters the polarity field of the other.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] The attraction allows closer spacing between molecules than is usually found in non-polar mixtures.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] Thus, alc/vol is not the same as volume fraction expressed as a percentage.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] Volume fraction, which is widely used in chemistry (commonly denoted as v/v), is defined as the volume of a particular component divided by the sum of all components in the mixture when they are measured separately.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] For example, to make 100 mL of 50% alc/vol ethanol solution, water would be added to 50 mL of ethanol to make up exactly 100 mL.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] Whereas to make a 50% v/v ethanol solution, 50 mL of ethanol and 50 mL of water could be mixed but the resulting volume of solution will measure less than 100 mL due to the change of volume on mixing, and will contain a higher concentration of ethanol.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] The difference is not large, with the maximum difference being less than 2.5%, and less than 0.5% difference for concentrations under 20%.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] Some drinks have requirements of alcoholic content in order to be certified as a certain alcohol brand or label.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] For example, in the United Kingdom, the United States, Canada and European Union whisky is legally required to be no less than 40% ABV bottled.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] Low-alcohol beers (<0.5) are considered in some countries such as Iran as permitted (halal) despite alcohol being banned.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] However, the level of alcohol-free beers is typically the lowest commercially sold 0.05.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] It is near impossible for a healthy person to become intoxicated drinking low-alcohol drinks.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] The low concentration severely limits the rate of intake, which is easily dispatched by human metabolism.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] Quickly drinking 1.5 L of 0.4% alc/vol beer in an hour resulted in a maximum of 0.0056% BAC in a study of German volunteers.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] Healthy human kidneys can only excrete 0.8–1.0 L of water per hour, making water intoxication likely to set in before any alcoholic intoxication.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] The process of ethanol fermentation will slow down and eventually come to a halt as the alcohol produced becomes too concentrated for the yeast to tolerate, defining an upper limit of alc/vol for non-distilled alcoholic drinks.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] The typical tolerance for beer yeasts is at 8–12%, while wine yeasts typically range from 14–18%, with speciality ones reaching 20% alc/vol.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] Any higher would require distillation, producing liquor.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] Details about typical amounts of alcohol contained in various beverages can be found in the articles about them.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] During the production of wine and beer, yeast is added to a sugary solution.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] During fermentation, the yeasts consume the sugars and produce alcohol.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] The density of sugar in water is greater than the density of alcohol in water.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] A hydrometer is used to measure the change in specific gravity (SG) of the solution before and after fermentation.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] The volume of alcohol in the solution can then be estimated.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] There are a number of empirical formulae which brewers and winemakers use to estimate the alcohol content of the liquor made.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] Specific gravity is the density of a liquid relative to that of water, i.e., if the density of the liquid is 1.05 times that of water, it has a specific gravity of 1.05.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] In UK brewing usage, it is customary to regard the reference value for water to be 1000, so the specific gravity of the same example beer would be quoted as 1050.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] The formulas here assume that the former definition is used for specific gravity.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] During ethanol fermentation the yeast converts one mole of sugar into two moles of alcohol.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] where 46.069 is the molar mass of ethanol and 180.156 is the molar mass of glucose and fructose.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] SG can be measured using an hydrometer and Brix can be calculated from SG.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] SG drop is how much the SG decreased during fermentation (at 20 degree C).
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] The factor 135 is most accurate in the center of the SG drop range of 0.000 to 0.179.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] Advanced formula derived from Carl Balling empirical formulas.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] The formula compensates for changes in SG with changes in alcohol concentration and for the fact that not all sugar is converted into alcohol.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] where SG final is the specific gravity when fermentation ends, Plato start is the sugar by weight when fermentation begins, Plato final is the sugar by weight when fermentation ends.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] Brix can be used instead of Plato as they are nearly identical.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] Another way of specifying the amount of alcohol content is alcohol *proof*, which in the United States is twice the alcohol-by-volume (alc/vol) number.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] This may lead to confusion over similar products bought in varying regions that have different names on country-specific labels.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] For example, Stroh rum that is 80% ABV is advertised and labeled as *Stroh 80* when sold in Europe, but is named *Stroh 160* when sold in the United States.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] In the United Kingdom, proof is 1.75 times the number (expressed as a percentage).
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] For example, 40% alc/vol is 80 proof in the US and 70 proof in the UK.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] However, since 1980, alcohol proof in the UK has been replaced by alc/vol as a measure of alcohol content, avoiding confusion between the UK and US proof standards.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] In the United States, Arkansas, Kansas, Mississippi, South Carolina, and Tennessee regulate and tax alcoholic beverages according to **alcohol by weight** (**ABW**), expressed as a percentage of total mass.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] The alc/vol value of a beverage is always higher than the ABW.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] Because ABW measures the proportion of the drink's mass which is alcohol, while alc/vol is the proportion of the drink's volume which is alcohol, the two values are in the same proportion as the drink's density is with the density of alcohol.
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] At relatively low alc/vol, the alcohol percentage by weight is about 4/5 of the alc/vol (e.g., 3.2% ABW is about 4% alc/vol).
[src:ale/alcohol-by-volume] However, because of the miscibility of alcohol and water, the conversion factor is not constant but rather depends upon the concentration of alcohol.
[src:ale/ale] As with most beers, ale typically has a bittering agent to balance the malt and act as a preservative.
[src:ale/ale] Ale was originally bittered with gruit, a mixture of herbs or spices boiled in the wort before fermentation, before hops replaced gruit as the bittering agent.
[src:ale/ale] In England, however, it was also common to brew ale without adding herbs.
[src:ale/ale] The word *ale* comes into English from its ancestor-language, Proto-Germanic.
[src:ale/ale] English belongs to the West Germanic branch of Proto-Germanic, and some other languages in this branch also attest to the word: Middle Dutch *āle* and *ael*, and the Old Saxon word *alo-fat* 'ale-cup'.
[src:ale/ale] The word is also found throughout the North Germanic languages, almost certainly appearing in ancient runic inscriptions in the form *alu*, and subsequently in Old Norse as *ǫl*.
[src:ale/ale] Through linguistic reconstruction it is possible to infer that the Common Germanic form of this word was **alúþ-*.
[src:ale/ale] According to the third edition of the *Oxford English Dictionary*, however, the origin of this word is 'uncertain and disputed'.
[src:ale/ale] Research by Harald Bjorvand, however, has favoured the following explanation: the Germanic word **alú-þ-* descends from the Indo-European word ***olú-t-* (from an earlier Indo-European base **h₂elut-*), which originally meant 'golden or reddish colour'.
[src:ale/ale] Other Indo-European words related to this root include Old Indic *aruṣá-* ('reddish'; the *r* comes from an earlier *l*, **alu-sá-*) and Old High German *elo* ('yellowy, pale yellow, reddish yellow, tawny').
[src:ale/ale] The Indo-European word **olú-t-* then came to refer specifically to ale because this is its colour, giving rise to both the Germanic word **alú-þ-* and the Ossetic word *æluton*.
[src:ale/ale] In this account, the Indo-European word **olú-t-* was also borrowed into the Finnic languages, giving Finnish *olut* and Estonian *õlu*.
[src:ale/ale] The relationship of similar words in the Slavonic languages (such as Old Bulgarian *olu* 'cider', Slovenian *ol* 'beer') and the Baltic languages (Lithuanian *alus*, Latvian *alus*, 'beer', Old Prussian *alu* 'mead') remains uncertain.
[src:ale/ale] Ale was an important source of nutrition in the medieval world.
[src:ale/ale] It was one of three main sources of grain in the diet at the start of the fourteenth century in England, along with pottage and bread.
[src:ale/ale] Scholars believe grains accounted for around 80% of the calorie intake of agricultural workers and 75% for soldiers - even nobles received around 65% of their calories from grains.
[src:ale/ale] Small beer, also known as table beer or mild beer, which was highly nutritious, contained just enough alcohol to act as a preservative, and provided hydration without intoxicating effects.
[src:ale/ale] Small beer would have been consumed daily by almost everyone, including children, in the medieval world, with higher-alcohol ales served for recreational purposes.
[src:ale/ale] The lower cost for proprietors combined with the lower taxes levied on small beer inevitably led to the selling of some beer labeled "strong beer" that had actually been diluted with small beer.
[src:ale/ale] Records from the Middle Ages show that ale was consumed in huge quantities.
[src:ale/ale] In 1272, a husband and wife who retired at Selby Abbey were given 2 gallons of ale per day with two loaves of white bread and one loaf of brown bread.
[src:ale/ale] Monks at Westminster Abbey consumed 1 gallon of ale each day.
[src:ale/ale] In 1299, Henry de Lacy's household purchased an average of 85 gallons of ale daily and in 1385–86 Framlingham Castle consumed 78 gallons per day.
[src:ale/ale] Brewing ale in the Middle Ages was a local industry primarily pursued by women.
[src:ale/ale] Brewsters, or alewives, would brew in the home for both domestic consumption and small scale commercial sale.
[src:ale/ale] Brewsters provided a substantial supplemental income for families; however, only in select few cases, as was the case for widows, was brewing considered the primary income of the household.
[src:ale/ale] From the mid-17th century, strong ales became particularly fashionable.
[src:ale/ale] They were known by names such as Huff-Cap, Nippitate and Hum-Cup, so called because it caused "a humming sensation in the head".
[src:ale/ale] Strong ale, like wine, was typically decanted due to the high sediment content into small glasses, which were better suited to the high ABV ale.
[src:ale/ale] Modern ale is typically fermented at temperatures between 15 and 24 °C (59 and 75 °F).
[src:ale/ale] At temperatures above 24 °C (75 °F) the yeast can produce significant amounts of esters and other secondary flavour and aroma products, and the result is often a beer with slightly "fruity" compounds resembling those found in fruits, such as apple, pear, pineapple, banana, plum, cherry, or prune.
[src:ale/ale] When ale ferments, it naturally creates two prevalent byproducts, those being Sulfur Dioxide (SO2) and Hydrogen Sulfide (H2S).
[src:ale/ale] Each of these compounds affects the product in different ways, and each can be managed before and during the fermenting process to create different flavours and benefits for the ale.
[src:ale/ale] Sulfur Dioxide is a product of some of the initial ingredients of ale and is produced during the fermentation of the wort.
[src:ale/ale] Sulfur Dioxide helps to increase an ale's shelf life; however, it naturally occurs in foods when they become old, so many people react negatively to its smell and can even be viewed as an allergen in some countries.
[src:ale/ale] During the stages of fermentation of ale, the production of SO2 works as an antioxidant, a preservative, and, in addition, it works to fight bacteria.
[src:ale/ale] Throughout the fermentation process, one of the ways in which brewers can control the levels of SO2 is through temperature during brewing, and another way to preserve that reaction is by tempering with the temperature at which the product is stored.
[src:ale/ale] The cooler it is stored, the more SO2 is preserved, which helps the ale keep its flavour.
[src:ale/ale] When an ale becomes stale from oxidation, it loses its natural flavours; it could taste like any multitude of different undesirable things, depending on the initial flavour of the ale.
[src:ale/ale] Some of the most common tastes for people are that of sherry, where the flavours have gotten negatively sweeter, or that of cardboard or paper, where it tastes stale and bland.
[src:ale/ale] Hydrogen sulfide is another byproduct of fermentation.
[src:ale/ale] In yeast strains, it helps the yeast grow and also works as an antioxidant later in the fermentation process.
[src:ale/ale] Having a chemical compound including sulfur, however, means that it has a pungent smell that people often associate with rotten eggs, which can later affect the produced ale negatively, so producing and managing a finite amount of hydrogen sulfide is very important in the fermenting of ale.
[src:ale/ale] When controlled, the amount of H2S is generally unnoticeable and does not affect the overall smell or taste, but still does its job of keeping the shelf life of the ale.
[src:ale/ale] While making ale, sugar can be added either during the boiling stage or the fermenting stage; however, both times lead to similar outcomes, just at different levels of effectiveness.
[src:ale/ale] The benefits of adding sugar to a brew can be to increase the overall APV levels of the brew and the flavour at the end of the brewing process.
[src:ale/ale] Due to the higher APV, however, the body of the beer can often be left thinner, having a water-like consistency.
[src:ale/ale] Both the factors of APV levels and flavour depend on what type of sugar you are adding, and oftentimes, when you add them in the process.
[src:ale/ale] Generally, the later a sugar is added to the brew, the more prominent the flavour will be.
[src:ale/ale] Sugar can be added so long as it is fermentable, which most common sugars are.
[src:ale/ale] Generally, brewers will add different syrups, saps, honeys, and syrups to their ale.
[src:ale/ale] Flocculation is the tendency for the yeast to conglomerate into large masses at the top and bottom of the fermentation tank at the end of the fermentation process.
[src:ale/ale] This selective trait in the yeast came about as the majority of the yeast that gets repurposed is that which aggregates and gets easily removed.
[src:ale/ale] This selective trait is gradually characterized in most yeast as the yeast that exhibits this behavior lasts a greater number of generations.
[src:ale/ale] "Real ale" is a British term, coined by the Campaign for Real Ale, for cask and bottle-conditioned beer.
[src:ale/ale] The following list breaks the many various ales into separate, diverse categories.
[src:ale/ale] The ales listed are categorized into their respective style groups of origin and accompanied by information regarding the specific brew.
[src:ale/ale] For further classification, more comprehensive information can be found in the Brewers Association Style Guide.
[src:ale/ale] In 18th-century England, brewers coined the term "pale ale" to distinguish this golden-hued ale from the more prevalent dark ales of the time.
[src:ale/ale] The use of hops during fermentation introduces a distinctive bitter aroma, while the general absence of diacetyl groups and the presence of esters contribute to a sweeter and fruitier flavour compared to other ales.
[src:ale/ale] The average alcohol by volume (ABV) of these ales ranges from 3.2% to 5.3%.
[src:ale/ale] Scotch ale, also known as "wee heavy", boasts an exceptionally malty taste accented by sweet malty undertones due to the heavy concentration of esters.
[src:ale/ale] Generally low in bitterness, it exhibits a deep caramel colour, the shade of which may vary depending on the brewing techniques.
[src:ale/ale] They have a relatively high ABV, falling between 6.6% and 8.5%.
[src:ale/ale] British-style summer ale is characteristically lighter in gold colour.
[src:ale/ale] Filled with esters, this beer yields a fruity flavour and maintains a subdued yet weak profile in bitterness and hop.
[src:ale/ale] The ale is traditionally high in carbonation due to its respective brewing techniques.
[src:ale/ale] Falling within the standard ABV range of 3.7% to 5.1% aligns with most beer's typical potency.
[src:ale/ale] Old ale is classified as an intensely dark red ale.
[src:ale/ale] It is said to have a fruity aroma, with brewers occasionally adding caramel to sweeten the product.
[src:ale/ale] The hop flavouring and bitterness of an old ale are relatively low compared to other types of categorized ales.
[src:ale/ale] Adequately brewing an old ale involves an aging process spanning a few years.
[src:ale/ale] Upon completion, it yields an extremely sweet drink comparable to wine.
[src:ale/ale] The final ABV of the ale ranges from 5.0% to 9.3%, with higher percentages correlating to the amount of sugar added during fermentation.
[src:ale/ale] Brown ale, distinguished by its dark hue, is commonly enriched with a blend of roasted and caramel malts, leading to a distinctively unique toffee-flavoured ale.
[src:ale/ale] Both esters and diacetyl are found in low levels, contributing to the beer's unique taste.
[src:ale/ale] The ABV of brown ales typically ranges between 4.2% and 6.0%.
[src:ale/ale] Barley wine is known for its balance of flavour and high alcohol content.
[src:ale/ale] The ale's colour varies widely depending on the duration of its age, as its flavour profile evolves dramatically over time.
[src:ale/ale] Low levels of diacetyl and carbonation are found in all barely wines, while esters are found in high quantities, contributing to a low bitter fruity flavour and aroma.
[src:ale/ale] The flavours of barley wines are diverse, ranging from bread-like to hints of molasses and toffee.
[src:ale/ale] They have an unusually high ABV, ranging from 8.5% to 12.2%.
[src:ale/ale] India pale ale, commonly shortened to IPA, is a hoppy pale ale which was originally shipped to colonial India.
[src:ale/ale] Its high hop content prevented spoilage during the long sea course from England to India.
[src:ale/ale] IPA is full bodied and hoppy, it is amber coloured and usually somewhat opaque.
[src:ale/ale] The ABV of IPA can fall within the range of 4.5–20%.
[src:ale/ale] Amber ale is an American craft beer named after the hue it possesses from being flavoured using caramel malt.
[src:ale/ale] The ale is brewed with an assortment of hops and has a balanced flavour.
[src:ale/ale] It maintains a low level of esters and lacks any trace of diacetyl, leading to a moderately bitter and slightly fruity undertone.
[src:ale/ale] The ABV of amber ales ranges anywhere from 4.4% to 5.4%.
[src:ale/ale] Sour ale, more commonly known as wild ale, is characterized by a unique sour flavour, produced during fermentation when acid-producing bacteria like lactobacillus or acetobacter feed on sugars.
[src:ale/ale] The acidity produced comes from mild concentrations of lactic or acetic acid and further develops during the aging process.
[src:ale/ale] Utilizing wooden bourbon barrels imbued with either vanillin or sherry plays a crucial role in augmenting the beer's flavour complexity during aging.
[src:ale/ale] The presence of esters and diacetyl fluctuates depending on the sought-after flavour profile of the brew.
[src:ale/ale] The final ABV varies widely depending on the length and methods used during brewing.
[src:ale/ale] Table beer typically has a low ABV of around 0.5% - 2.0%.
[src:ale/ale] Popular in Eastern Europe, these beverages are brewed with malt barley, wheat, oats, or rye.
[src:ale/ale] They are commonly flavoured with additive sugar and either orange or lemon peels to yield a citrus-like flavouring.
[src:ale/ale] Session ale, named for its purpose of being enjoyed within a single "session" without inducing significant intoxication, features a low ABV, typically ranging from 3% to 5%.
[src:ale/ale] Though they share similarities with table beers, they maintain a higher alcohol percentage.
[src:ale/ale] They are characterized by a balanced flavour profile, as the production method does not stray far from traditional ale brewing.
[src:ale/ale] Esters may be present in medium quantities adding sweetness to the final flavour, while diacetyl is non-existent.
[src:ale/ale] Most commercially available ales fall under the distinction of session ales due to their cost-effective ability to be brewed in mass.
[src:ale/ale] The flavour profile of dark ale is characterized by a malty sweetness resulting from the abundance of esters in the brew.
[src:ale/ale] A discernible spiciness is attributed to yeast-derived phenolic compounds present in moderate quantities.
[src:ale/ale] Depending on the brand, the beer tends to have a modest level of bitterness owing to the hops during fermentation.
[src:ale/ale] The aroma of the brew is described as subtle yet persistent, due to phenol compounds.
[src:ale/ale] In terms of ABV, dark ale ranks notably high compared to other brews, ranging from 7.1% to 11.2%, often veiled by its diverse flavour profile.
[src:ale/ale] Bière de Garde is a hybrid beer whose name translates from French to English as “Beer for Keeping”.
[src:ale/ale] The ale is low to moderate in esters and contains a similar malt sweetness to most other ales.
[src:ale/ale] The ale's ABV ranges from 4.4% to 8% and has a range of appearances, with its primary descriptions being “Light Amber, Chestnut Brown, or Red.” While most popular in France, this style has become much more frequent in the U.S. as the ale industry grows.
[src:ale/ale] Irish red ale is characterized by its definitive amber or dark red hue, having an ABV ranging from 4.0% to 4.8%, and having a standard approachable bitterness, all of which make this ale highly sessionable.
[src:ale/ale] Medium flavours of candy-like caramel malt distinguish the ale, and a tan foam forms at the top, due to the inclusion of roasted barley.
[src:ale/ale] Originating in the Düsseldorf region of Germany, Altbier pays homage to traditional brewing methods, with "alt" meaning old in English.
[src:ale/ale] The complexion ranges from light amber to a deep copper colour.
[src:ale/ale] Esters are present in low quantities, which is attributed to their lightly citrus profile, while diacetyls are completely absent.
[src:ale/ale] The ale boasts a moderate level of bitterness owing to hops utilized in fermentation.
[src:ale/ale] Its ultimate ABV falls within the range of 4.6% to 5.6%, aligning typically with other ales.
[src:ale/aleberry] Aleberry was often used as a domestic remedy for a cold.
[src:ale/aleberry] It is not only Strengthening, but very good against Colds and Rheums.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] An **alewife**, also **brewess** or **brewster**, was a woman who brewed ale for commercial sale.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Women have been active in brewing since before the process's industrialisation.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] The word "alewife" is first recorded in England in 1393 to mean "a woman that keeps an ale-house", synonymous with the word "brewster".
[src:ale/alewife-trade] "Alewife" is now commonly used in translations of ancient texts to refer to any woman who brewed and sold ale dating back to the beginning of recorded history.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Although the profession was later taken over by men, the original brewing profession back in ancient Mesopotamia was principally performed by women.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] The character of Siduri in the Epic of Gilgamesh appears as a divine alewife.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Women also brewed the majority of ale for both domestic and commercial use in England before the Black Death, and some women continued brewing into the 17th century.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Ale represented a key part of the medieval English diet as it was both the most affordable and clean beverage available.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] The precise amount of ale that was ingested daily is not known, but it appears to have been up to a gallon a day per person.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Because ale went sour within days after being brewed, constant production was necessary to meet demand.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Therefore, ale was produced in huge quantities by a relatively simple process that was widely known, although time intensive, most often using malted barley or oats.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] The ale trade in all of England was legally regulated by the Assize of Bread and Ale, "which linked the price of ale to the price of grain and which ordained public checks on the quality of the brew." Operating outside of this regulation was forbidden and handled severely by the courts.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Public records in the medieval period before the Black Death include regulatory legislation that treats brewing as a solely female profession, indicating that brewing ale was dominated by women.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] This female dominance of the trade likely evolved because it could be done in the home, supplemented other incomes, and was passed down from previous generations of women.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] The lack of needed specialization and physical location within the home made ale brewing an accessible trade for women to add income to the household in both towns and countryside communities.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Elite wives also apparently engaged in this activity in a supervisory capacity over their female servants without social stigma.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Records regarding medieval brewing often leave out the poorer families in which women were almost certainly brewing in small amounts for consumption and irregular sale, possibly because authorities focused only on regular brewing on a larger scale than many families could afford to produce.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Drinking alcohol daily was a common practice between 1300 and 1700.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] At this time, the quality of water was so poor that alcohol was preferred for taste.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Estimates find the average annual consumption of wine in France to be over 100 liters for the majority of the period 1300–1700s.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Drinking was so prevalent at the time that workers could request to be paid in alcohol instead of monetary wages.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] While they drank alcohol, medieval Europeans did not drink so heavily for inebriation but rather as sustenance for daily life in place of other common drinks such as water.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Because winemaking was a very involved process, and hopped beer had not yet spread from the Netherlands and Belgium, ale and hard cider became popular among the lower classes in medieval England.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Medieval ale spoiled quickly, making mass production difficult and resulting in localized industries made up of many small ale producers throughout medieval towns.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] For example, in 1577 there was 1 alehouse for every 142 inhabitants per town.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] The structure of the ale industry meant that women could play an integral part in brewing, selling, and serving ale.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] By the late 15th century, hopped beer began supplanting ale as a popular drink in medieval England.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Beer brewed with hops was previously only popular in the Netherlands and Belgium, but it gained popularity because it kept fresh longer, was easier to transport, and was used as a military drink more frequently.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Because brewers in the Low Countries considered brewing a male trade, women rarely engaged in medieval beer brewing as the industry grew.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] As the beer industry grew, the female-centric ale market was supplanted in part by the male-centric beer market.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] As a trade in medieval Europe, ale brewing offered women a relatively lucrative and stable career.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Even as the industry underwent multiple economic changes in the Late Middle Ages, female brewers and alewives generally found stable work in the trade, particularly when compared to other contemporary female trades.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Women's role in the medieval ale industry likely grew out of the traditional household responsibilities of wives and daughters, who had to brew ale to feed to their families.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] To turn a profit, early medieval women became "small-scale retailers" by selling goods they already produced for private consumption.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Brewing and selling ale (also known as tippling or tapping) enabled women to work for and achieve "good profits, social power, and some measure of independence from men" that other trades at the time did not.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Medieval women, particularly unmarried, young, and widowed women, were almost exclusively barred from many methods of self-support.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Many medieval industries relied on land ownership, long apprenticeships, and wage work, all of which consistently discriminated against female participation or required heavy male presence for women who did enter these industries.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] As a result, most women's work in the late medieval period was low skilled, low status, and low profit.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Comparatively, brewing and tippling were predominantly female trades that women could operate independently or in equal conjunction with their husband.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Following the Black Plague of 1347–50, the brewing trade underwent significant changes that made it a commercialized and specialized trade.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Medieval society underwent many changes following the Plague.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Due to these changes, the ale market transformed from an industry dominated by occasional, home-brewing married and non-married women to a commercialized, professionalized, and male-governed mainstream trade.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] As a result, female brewers and alewives in the late 14th and 15th centuries faced one of two fates: greater profit, or marginalization within the trade.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Women who managed to remain in the ale trade were usually married, widowed, or had unusual access to money and capital for a craftswoman.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] The rest of the women engaged in the ale trade, particularly occasional or part-time brewsters, lost the ease of market entry and economic stability they formerly had as ale brewers.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] These women either found other trades or methods for self-support (marriage, prostitution, etc.), or remained in the ale trade as tipplers and tapsters employed by male brewers.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] By the 16th century, guilds also centralized and regulated brewing more heavily, which also contributed to the decline of women in the ale trade.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] The expansion and professionalization of the trade less suited the short-term readily available jobs that women tended to take on while maintaining their roles as wives and mothers.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] The trade's changes also enabled medieval men to enter a trade previously dominated by women.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Unlike women, men had the legal, capital, social, and cultural resources to command a quickly commercializing industry.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] While ale brewing and selling was a lucrative and stable trade for all classes of medieval townswomen throughout the Middle Ages, married women and non-married women had differing experiences within this trade.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Non-married women, including single young women, widows, single mothers, concubines, and deserting or deserted wives, at times engaged in the brewing trade and made enough to support themselves independently.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Most non-married women worked in brewing only occasionally, turning to it to support themselves temporarily – before marriage, in between marriages, during times of poverty, and during widowhood.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Some non-married women did pursue the trade more permanently, but this was rare.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Medieval records show some rare examples of permanent brewers with no mention of a husband (implying single status), including Emma Kempstere of Brigstock, Maud London of Oxford, and Margery de Brundall of Norwich who lived and brewed in the 14th and 15th centuries.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] According to non-married brewsters' tax records, profits, and legal statuses as recorded in medieval guild and tax collecting records, brewsters lived more independently and had a higher standard of living when compared to other non-married medieval women.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Compared to married female brewsters, non-married brewsters brewed ale less frequently and with less consistency over time.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] They also earned less than a married woman operating in a married household or in business with her husband.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Until the mid-14th Century, ale was mostly produced in the home, and was sold and consumed in either the home or the local alehouse.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Non-married brewsters typically brewed and sold their product from the home, as they lacked the legal or guild standing and money to have their own alehouse.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] They also rarely had the resources to pay for brewing apprentices or servants and were less likely to have large families to help with the work of brewing.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] These factors limited the profitability of single brewsters compared to other brewers, and made participation in the industry a less consistent, more occasional practice by non-married brewsters.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Between the 15th and 16th centuries, after the Plague brought the commercialization of brewing, non-married brewsters began slowly disappearing from the trade.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Non-married brewsters' part-time or occasional status, lack of access to capital, and lack of a centralized physical location in which to sell their product led to their marginalization by the 16th century.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] By this time, many non-married women seeking to participate in brewing and the ale trade became tapsters, tipplers, and wageworkers in brewhouses for commercial male brewers.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] A small minority of non-married women may have remained brewsters in their own right during this time.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] For example, there is evidence that some women were members of the London Brewers Guild in their own right in the 15th century; most were widows continuing the trade of their deceased husbands, but some had no record of male relatives and were likely single women.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Married brewsters typically brewed in tandem with their husbands, as relatively equal partners in business and production.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Because many medieval trades, and brewing specifically, were organized around the household, married brewsters could brew and sell ale for large profits.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Accordingly, married brewsters likely had more access to capital and servants through their husbands' economic endeavors, lands, or inheritance.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] This allowed married brewsters to sustain, expand, and stabilize their trade.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] As a result of their stability and access to resources, married brewsters "reaped considerable profit from the ale market", earning more than non-married brewsters and more than married women in other trades.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Prior to the 16th century, wives and husbands divided the day-to-day operations of brewing relatively equally, with wives working independently from rather than subordinate to their husbands.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] The division of labor between brewing couples was typically split between public and managerial roles.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] The husband almost exclusively held the public responsibilities, including guild activity and serving as the legal representative of the establishment.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Wives typically had jurisdiction over the responsibilities of the "conjugal household", which included the physical brewing, management of any laborers, and, if the trade was run out of an alehouse, management of the alehouse itself.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] As evidenced by records of alewives' medieval guild payments, wives often paid large guild taxes that were listed independently of their brewer husbands.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] This indicates that women were given credit as equal partners with their husbands for a high profitability.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Following the industry changes in wake of the Black Death, married women remained actors in the newly commercialized trade even as single women disappeared.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Commercialized brewing required even greater resources and household investment than before, which married women had access to via their husbands.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] As commercialization and higher profitability brought growing numbers of men into the trade, married women's place in brewing was strengthened, although their work within the trade changed.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] With the departure of most non-married women from the ale trade, independent brewing by all women became less commonly accepted.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Married female brewers after the 14th century became less independent from their husbands, but remained in the trade as unofficial managers, brewing laborers, and tapsters in their husbands' alehouses.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Brewsters became the scapegoat for the brewing community as a whole for the vices that the medieval world feared from the production of alcohol.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] In 1540, the city of Chester ordered that no women between the ages of 14 and 40 would be permitted to sell ale, in the hopes of limiting the trade to only women above or below an age of sexual desirability.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Women in brewing and selling of ale were accused of being disobedient to their husbands, sexually deviant, but also frequently cheating their customers with watered-down ale and higher prices.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] While a 1324 record of offenses of brewers and tipplers in Oxford cites that offenses by women and men were relatively equal, most representations of ale sellers only negatively represented the women.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] In popular culture of the period as well, the alewife was a common figure of comical condemnation.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] She was depicted in Dooms or church murals as someone who belonged in hell.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Poems such as John Skelton's *The Tunning of Elynour Rummyng*, *The Tale of Beryn* and Mother Bunch of *Pasquil's Jests* all depicted as repulsive figures.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Either sexually promiscuous themselves, or employers of prostitutes, the alewife was frequently associated with sinful behavior.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Elynour Rummyng produces a parody of a mass while luring men away from church.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] The character of Kit in *The Tale of Beryn* seduces one man while flirting with another all for the purpose of selling ale.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Mother Bunch's famous ale is said to be made from her nose.
[src:ale/alewife-trade] Whether laughed at with the alewives or against them, the language of these poems suggest that they were intended for a general public rather than exclusively the courts, making the popularity of the flawed alewife a common role of society.
[src:ale/altbier] Altbier is usually a dark, copper colour.
[src:ale/altbier] It is fermented at a moderate temperature using a top-fermenting yeast—which gives its flavour some fruitiness.
[src:ale/altbier] Because Altbier is then matured at a cooler temperature, its flavour is more akin to lager beer styles than is the norm for top-fermented beers (such as British pale ale).
[src:ale/altbier] It generally has an ABV between 4.3% and 5.5%.
[src:ale/altbier] The first producer to use the name Altbier—to contrast its top-fermenting beer with the bottom-fermenting kinds—was the Schumacher brewery of Düsseldorf, that opened in 1838.
[src:ale/altbier] Mass-market brewers of Altbier include Diebels and the Radeberger Gruppe under the brands Schlösser Alt and Hansa Alt.
[src:ale/altbier] These are complemented by small breweries in Düsseldorf and other nearby cities.
[src:ale/altbier] Some Altbier breweries have a tradition of producing a stronger version, called *sticke alt*, coming from a local dialect word meaning "secret".
[src:ale/altbier] Originally made as a special reserve beer intended for the brewers' own consumption, today it is generally a seasonal or special occasion brew.
[src:ale/altbier] There exists a regional rivalry between the drinkers of Altbier in the Düsseldorf area and the drinkers of Kölsch beer in the Cologne (Köln) area.
[src:ale/altbier] A beer variety associated with the Lower Rhine region, Altbier is especially found in Düsseldorf, Krefeld, and Mönchengladbach.
[src:ale/altbier] Füchschen, Uerige, Schlüssel and Kürzer are all brewed and sold in the Altstadt (Old Town).
[src:ale/altbier] Schumacher is between the Altstadt and the main train station (Hauptbahnhof), although it also has a pub in the Altstadt, Im Goldenen Kessel, across the street from Schlüssel.
[src:ale/altbier] Each brewpub produces a seasonal "Sticke" variant in small quantities, though the names vary: Schlüssel spells it "Stike", without the "c", while Schumacher calls its special beer "Latzenbier", meaning "slat beer", possibly because the kegs from which it was poured had been stored on raised shelves.
[src:ale/altbier] Füchschen's seasonal is its Weihnachtsbier (Christmas beer), available in bottles starting mid-November, and served in the brewpub on Christmas Eve.
[src:ale/altbier] Altbier is somewhat similar to Cologne's native beer style *Kölsch*, being warm-fermented at a lower temperature than British ales, and Altbier proper is also brewed as "Ehrenfelder Alt", in Cologne's smallest brewery "Braustelle".
[src:ale/altbier] Pinkus Müller brewery in Münster produces an Altbier which is quite different to the Düsseldorf style, being pale and slightly tart.
[src:ale/altbier] Altbier has been produced in the city of Venlo in the Netherlands since at least 1753.
[src:ale/altbier] Venlo is on the border to Germany approximately 50 km (30 miles) from Düsseldorf.
[src:ale/altbier] The beer was produced up until the Second World War, but then had a hiatus until its revival in 1983.
[src:ale/altbier] It is produced by the Lindeboom brewery, who bought the recipe in 2001.
[src:ale/altbier] Altbier is brewed in small quantities in Austria, Switzerland, Hungary, Liechtenstein, the UK, the United States, Canada, Australia by Tooheys in Sydney New South Wales, New Zealand, Japan, South Africa, Norway, Brazil and Australia.
[src:ale/altbier] Versions of altbier are brewed in the United States, though not always to traditional recipes, with Widmer Brothers often considered the first American brewer to produce the style.
[src:ale/alu-runic] The sequence ***alu*** (ᚨᛚᚢ) is found in numerous Elder Futhark runic inscriptions of Germanic Iron Age Scandinavia (and more rarely in early Anglo-Saxon England) between the 3rd and the 8th century.
[src:ale/alu-runic] The word usually appears either alone (such as on the Elgesem runestone) or as part of an apparent formula (such as on the Lindholm "amulet" (DR 261) from Scania, Sweden).
[src:ale/alu-runic] The symbols represent the runes Ansuz, Laguz, and Uruz.
[src:ale/alu-runic] The origin and meaning of the word are matters of dispute, though a general agreement exists among scholars that the word represents an instance of historical runic magic or is a metaphor (or metonym) for it.
[src:ale/alu-runic] It is the most common of the early runic charm words.
[src:ale/alu-runic] The word disappears from runic inscriptions shortly after the Migration Period, even before the Christianization of Scandinavia.
[src:ale/alu-runic] It may have lived on beyond this period with an increasing association with ale, appearing in stanzas 7 and 19 of the Old Norse poem *Sigrdrífumál*, compiled in the 13th century *Poetic Edda*, where knowledge of invocative "ale runes" (Old Norse ölrúnar) is imparted by the Valkyrie Sigrdrífa.
[src:ale/alu-runic] Theories have been suggested that the unique term *ealuscerwen* (possibly "pouring away of *alu*"), used to describe grief or terror in the epic poem *Beowulf*, recorded around the 9th to 11th century, may be directly related.
[src:ale/alu-runic] Although the literal meaning of the word *alu* is generally accepted to be "ale," i.e.
[src:ale/alu-runic] "intoxicating beverage," researchers have found it necessary to look deeper into the significance of the term.
[src:ale/alu-runic] Raetian North Etruscan dedicatory votive objects have been discovered featuring *alu* where the term means "dedication".
[src:ale/alu-runic] Connections have been proposed between these objects and the term *alu* found on runic inscriptions.
[src:ale/alu-runic] Theories have been proposed that the term was loaned into Runic usage from this source.
[src:ale/alu-runic] The inscription *alu* appears on the following bracteates: G 205, DR BR6, DR BR13, DR BR25, DR BR42, DR BR54, DR BR59, DR BR63A, DR BR67, DR EM85;123, and DR NOR2002;10.
[src:ale/alu-runic] A gold bracteate (G 205) discovered in Djupbrunns, Hogrän, Sweden reads simply *Alu* and dates from around 400 CE.
[src:ale/alu-runic] The bracteate was discovered in the same location as another gold bracteate (G 204) from a considerably younger date that features the inscription *ek erilaz*.
[src:ale/alu-runic] Today the bracteate is located in Swedish History Museum, Stockholm, Sweden.
[src:ale/alu-runic] A fragment of a bracteate (DR BR6) discovered in Skrydstrup, South Jutland, Denmark bears the term *Alu*.
[src:ale/alu-runic] The fragment dates from around 400 to 650 CE.
[src:ale/alu-runic] Today the bracteate is housed in the National Museum of Denmark in Copenhagen, Denmark.
[src:ale/alu-runic] A bracteate discovered on the island of Funen, Denmark features incomprehensible and meaningful text.
[src:ale/alu-runic] The bracteate is housed with many others at the National Museum of Denmark.
[src:ale/alu-runic] What is transcribed as **a--** above has been tentatively read as **alu**.
[src:ale/alu-runic] The word **houaz** has previously been interpreted as corresponding to Old Norse *hávi* "the high one", a name of Odin, but more recent scholarship instead prefers a reading **horaz** 'dear, beloved'.
[src:ale/alu-runic] The Uppåkra bracteate (DR NOR2002;10), a C-bracteate found in Uppåkra, Scania, Sweden during a search with a metal detector in 2000.
[src:ale/alu-runic] The bracteate bears a Proto-Norse runic inscription.
[src:ale/alu-runic] The bracteate depicts a man's head over a four-legged animal.
[src:ale/alu-runic] The A inscription (first part, **sima-ina**) is placed over the back part of the head, while the B inscription (second part, **alu**) is placed over the animal's front legs.
[src:ale/alu-runic] The inscription seems to belong to the big group of C-bracteates with more or less comprehensible charm words.
[src:ale/alu-runic] The third panel Elder Futhark inscriptions found on the 7th or 8th CE century Eggja stone discovered on the farm Eggja located in Sogn og Fjordane, Norway is often interpreted as reading *alu*.
[src:ale/alu-runic] An inscription reading simply "*alu*" is found on a stone discovered in a grave mound located by the farm of Elgesem, Vestfold, Norway, in 1870.
[src:ale/alu-runic] The Elgesem runestone, listed in the Rundata catalog as N KJ57 U, is dated to about 400 CE.
[src:ale/alu-runic] The stone is 172 centimeters tall and 90 centimeters wide, and the thickness is about 18 centimeters.
[src:ale/alu-runic] The inscription is written counter-clockwise and is to be read from the top downwards.
[src:ale/alu-runic] As the stone has been purposefully shaped, it has been suggested that the Elgesem runestone was a cult stone used as part of some ritual.
[src:ale/alu-runic] It has also been suggested that similar shaped cult stones are depicted on the Stora Hammars I, Ardre VIII and Tängelgårda IV image stones.
[src:ale/alu-runic] The Eketorp slate fragment (Öl ACTARC37;211 U) is a runestone that was found in Eketorp, Sweden and features an Elder Futhark inscription in Proto-Norse.
[src:ale/alu-runic] The Kinneve stone (Vg 134) is a stone fragment (measures 7,4 x 5,0 x 2,0 cm) of red soapstone dated to around 600 CE.
[src:ale/alu-runic] It was found by chaplain John Lagerblom in 1843 in a grave on the area of the rectory (*Prästgården*) of Kinneve socken, Sweden.
[src:ale/alu-runic] The stone is today housed in the collection of the Västergötland museum, Skara, Sweden.
[src:ale/alu-runic] siz (siR - the last rune is the *Algiz rune) has by Y.
[src:ale/alu-runic] Kodratoff been interpreted as the end of a name, and according to Kodratoff the *h* can represent the *Haglaz rune.
[src:ale/alu-runic] The Årstad stone (N KJ58) is a runestone found in 1855 on the Årstad farm in Rogaland, Norway.
[src:ale/alu-runic] It bears 18-20 runes of the Elder Futhark on three lines.
[src:ale/alu-runic] The second line reads **saralu**, which is by some scholars split into the words **sar** and **alu**.
[src:ale/alu-runic] Today the stone is housed in the Antiquities Collection at the Museum of Cultural History in Oslo.
[src:ale/alu-runic] The Nydam Arrow (DR 13) is an arrow discovered in Nydam Mose, South Jutland, Denmark that bears the inscription **lua** which has been interpreted as a distorted *alu*.
[src:ale/alu-runic] Today the arrow is housed in Museum für Vorgeschichtliche Altertümer in Kiel, Germany.
[src:ale/alu-runic] The Nydam arrow shafts (DR MS1995;344 and DR AUD1994;266) are two arrow shafts discovered in Nydam Mose, South Jutland, Denmark that bear the inscriptions **la** and **lua** respectively.
[src:ale/alu-runic] They have both been interpreted as *alu*, but it is not certain.
[src:ale/alu-runic] The arrow shafts are dated to around 300 to 350 CE.
[src:ale/alu-runic] Today they are housed at the National Museum of Denmark in Copenhagen.
[src:ale/alu-runic] The Nydam axe shaft (DR MS1995;341) is a wooden axe shaft discovered in Nydam Mose, South Jutland, Denmark that bears a runic inscription.
[src:ale/alu-runic] Today it is housed at the National Museum of Denmark in Copenhagen.
[src:ale/alu-runic] A 3rd century silver fibula (DR EM85;123) from Værløse, Zealand, Denmark features a runic inscription on its pinholder that simply reads "alugod" followed by a swastika.
[src:ale/alu-runic] The Værløse Fibula is housed at the National Museum of Denmark.
[src:ale/alu-runic] The Lindholm "amulet" (DR 261) is a bone piece found in Skåne, dated to the 2nd to 4th centuries.
[src:ale/alu-runic] The inscription contains the word *alu*.
[src:ale/alu-runic] Three 5th century cremation urns from Spong Hill, Norfolk, England bear the impression of the term *alu* by "the same runic stamp" in mirror-runes.
[src:ale/alu-runic] The Setre Comb is a comb from the 6th or early 7th century featuring runic inscriptions.
[src:ale/alu-runic] The comb is the subject of an amount of scholarly discourse as most experts accept the reading of the Germanic charm word *alu* and Nanna, though there exists questions as to if *Nanna* is the same figure as the goddess from later attestations.
